pull_request.title: JP-3664: Fix shuttrid negative values under numpy 2
pull_request.body:
<!-- If this PR closes a JIRA ticket, make sure the title starts with the JIRA issue number,
for example JP-1234: <Fix a bug> -->

Addresses [JP-3664](https://jira.stsci.edu/browse/JP-3664)

<!-- If this PR closes a GitHub issue, reference it here by its number -->
Closes #

<!-- describe the changes comprising this PR here -->
This PR addresses the fact that under numpy 2, the SHUTTRID values for NIRSPEC MOS data become negative for values >32767 due to their values being held in a signed short integer.  Casting to int64 before calculation (which is what is done implicitly under numpy 1.x) solves the problem.

<!-- if you can't perform these tasks due to permissions, please ask a maintainer to do them -->
## Tasks
- [ ] **request a review from someone specific**, to avoid making the maintainers review every PR
- [ ] add a build milestone, i.e. `Build 11.3` (use the [latest build](https://github.com/spacetelescope/jwst/milestones) if not sure)
- [ ] Does this PR change user-facing code / API? (if not, label with `no-changelog-entry-needed`)
  - [ ] write news fragment(s) in `changes/`: `echo "changed something" > changes/<PR#>.<changetype>.rst` (see below for change types) 
  - [ ] update or add relevant tests
  - [ ] update relevant docstrings and / or `docs/` page
  - [ ] [start a regression test](https://github.com/spacetelescope/RegressionTests/actions/workflows/jwst.yml) and include a link to the running job ([click here for instructions](https://github.com/spacetelescope/RegressionTests/blob/main/docs/running_regression_tests.md))
Regression tests were run with numpy 1.x (no differences) and 2.x (unrelated differences, SHUTTRID differences went away)

      - [ ] **after the reviewer has approved these changes**, run `okify_regtests` to update the truth files

issue.title: Keep copy of item in original location while dragging
issue.body:
I'm trying to achieve a behavior close to [Pragmatic Drag and drop](https://atlassian.design/components/pragmatic-drag-and-drop/examples#list), but cant figure out how to get it all the way working. 

[Here is a Repl](https://svelte.dev/playground/6c36e4d0b97847439a8541b4563c2f66?version=3.59.2) of my progress.

The issue is that it when grabbing an item from the middle it will disappear, causing all other items to shift. I want to avoid this and just show a lower opacity version until i drop it (like in Pragmatic Drag and drop). It also doesn't seem to show the drop indicator in the correct spot. I think this is because it is a different size than the actual dragged item.

Is there any example of doing something like this with svelte-dnd-action? If not, what would be the best approach to do this?

comment.body: Thinking about it further I wouldn't recommend using this library if you want this behaviour, which is basically the behaviour of the dnd implementation that's built into the browser. This library was written with the purpose of offering an alternative to that. It won't be easy and maybe not even possible to fully achieve this behaviour with code that was written specifically to create a much richer UX. You'll be basically fighting against the library
